#68058 Are you someone whose friends always seem to exclude you from things? Have you ever thought about why they don't invite you? People don't do things without a reason. There are really only two scenarios, with two clear courses of action to take. The first scenario is that this friend group is toxic and mean-spirited and exclude people from things for selfish/immature reasons that would persist regardless of your character. You should not be sad that they excluded you. I...n fact, you should be thanking your lucky stars that you dodged an entire hailstorm of bullets, and go and find some better friends. The second scenario is that there is nothing obviously wrong with the friend group. They are relatively decent people, and they get along with each other fine and hang out all the time, just not with you. Have you really, deeply thought about why this might be? Think about it - why would an entire friend group exclude someone who is kind and fun to be around? Would *you* want to avoid someone who was kind and fun to be around? People do not do things (or consistently "forget" to invite someone) for no reason - there's ALWAYS a reason. Thus the only possibility is that you are unkind or unpleasant to be around, or both (usually there is a strong correlation between these traits). In this case, you should not find it unreasonable that your so-called friends don't include you in things (since you'd probably do the same thing to someone you didn't like, wouldn't you?). Instead, if your friend group is a group that you care about and want to keep your connections with, you should try to become a kinder and more pleasant person that people would naturally want to hang out with - you can't really force anyone to want to be with you. It may take some time for them to notice, so you will need to be patient - of course, there is also no guarantee that they'll ever notice, but it's not like you've lost anything by becoming a kinder person. The other possibility (and by far the easiest thing for you to do) is that you don't change at all - in this case, you should be prepared to continue being excluded from things, and you should no longer be upset about it - after all, it's your choice. Tl;dr - if none of your friends want to hang out with you, either your friends all have problems, or you have problems. If your friends all have problems, then find better friends. If you have problems, then be a better person. Some notes: I've noticed that for a great deal of people (especially for people who post complaints on this page), whenever something doesn't go their way, they immediately think that it's everyone's problem but their own. This is a mindset that doesn't promote introspection or self-improvement, displays a lack of wisdom, and leads to things like MIT Confessions posts about problems that have very obvious (though not necessarily easy) solutions, if one took only a few minutes to think about it first.

first, because they deal with a lot of things for you. you don't have to spend 50+ hours apartment hunting and going through a broker, or have to furnish your own room, or call or hunt down your management company every time you need something, there's a convenient atlas request system, there's security workers to make sure the building is safe and let you in when necessary, and at least in tier ii dorms most of the appliances and electric systems are reasonably updated, i.e. you might not have really sketchy electric stoves where each burner needs to be turned just so in order to actually heat up. not to mention that building services even cleans your bathrooms for you. that's a lot of people they're paying to hopefully make your life a little easier. also, housing revenue margins are fairly slim because of maintenance costs. mit estimates a total $1.5b campus maintenance backlog (> $100/sq ft), a lot of which is student housing, and they keep building new dorms precisely because so many undergrad and grad students want to live on campus these days (part of which might be 2000s-era pushback against frat and alternative cultures, but anyway). aside from space/capacity issues, you're paying for these (intended) quality of life improvements and maybe the experience of mit dorm culture? I understand it's sad to leave that behind but ultimately if you'd rather not pay the premium and are able to dedicate a bit of bandwidth each week to your housing, consider not living on campus/shouldering mit's construction burdens and finding cheaper ways to be part of the mit community.

text: #67716 Course 9 here: I generally love course 9. It is run really well, the content is interesting, and you can kind of put in however much work you want. However, 9.40 can go suck its own dick.  First of all, it is a class that is literally computational cognition. It is a 6-9 class. Yet it is not required for course 6-9 and is instead only required for course 9 AND the course 9 minor. This leads to most people in the class complaining about it since none of us want to code ...and very few 6-9s taking it because of what they hear about it.  Second of all, the content is ridiculous. I am a double major in 18, and the content that we are learning is very much based in math, except that they don't have time to teach us the math, and try to get away with giving us a surface level understanding, then asking us to code it. It is nigh on impossible to code something that you don't understand. There should be many math prereqs to this class or it should be a grad class. The ideas are not difficult, they are just trying to do far too much and thus only teach us surface level anything but the psets and exams require an actual understanding of not just the ideas, but the math that the ideas are based upon. One of our problems on the first exam was to derive the 3D diffusion constant.  Third, although the exams are open note and we have two hours to do them, they are 17 pages long. Image a 17 page long PSET. I don't care if that's open note but you're not gonna finish it in two hours. They say the questions are straightforward, but again, that is based on the assumption that we understand the math basis that they skim over in class. It's not even that the math is too difficult, it's just that each new concept requires a new math concept that should take at least 3 lectures to teach just the math. And it is evident that the professors themselves do not really understand the math as they are not good at answering specific questions about it such as edge cases, derivations, etc and instead tell us not to worry about it. We are expected to develop an understanding of something without ever being shown where it comes from.  The psets are often unclear in their questions and so are the exams, and the two are completely different so there is no real method of studying for the exams by doing the PSETS. It feels like the coding portion of this class is entirely unnecessary particularly considering it is not a 6-9 requirement. Things in this class are not explained well.

#66389 As a recent MIT alum, I feel incredibly fortunate to be working for a non-tech company with global reach and a revenue north of $25 billion, the kind that most of the students here would just gloss over. I was never someone special during my time here and when I graduated I felt uncertain about my future in comparison to my peers. But now, I have been promoted quickly, as did many of my peers from prestigious schools like Stanford and Carnegie Mellon. People who attend...ed slightly less than elite universities like the University of Michigan, Georgia Tech, and Purdue, on the other hand, were not so lucky. Many of them are either languishing in lower positions or have been laid off during the current recession.  The work at this company is incredibly easy; it does not exceed the demands placed upon me by MIT as a junior, which admittedly is still a high bar all considered, and I never work more than 30 hours a week. It's almost criminal how much simpler my time here at this non-tech company is, considering that I make about double what my peers from Georgia Tech get with just ~4 years of experience. This is despite the fact that they work much longer hours. I believe a non-trivial portion of this is due to the company being dominated by MIT alumni who have gone on to become McKinsey alums and that 70% of the C-suite in my company are undergraduate alums, from either Stanford or MIT. If you’re anything like how I was during my time as an MIT student, this post will likely bring a tremendous sense of relief - but that relief will be quickly overshadowed by a heavy wave of guilt. We must not forget our privilege in this day and age: an MIT degree, particularly from Course 6, still serves as a coveted ‘golden ticket’ to the upper echelons of American society. There are only around a thousand humans in the world that get the opportunities every year in this planet inhabited by billions. Although the current recession has undoubtedly caused immense distress for many, for many MIT alum, it is merely a brief challenge. With this in mind, I implore you to think of ways in which you can give back to the community that has given you so much. It is likely that you will likely gain far more from this institution than you will ever give in return despite the less-than-idea food and the occasional rodent. It may be difficult to have this outlook now, but your future self will be grateful for keeping things in the right perspective.
